Part 1 Fourth Moments of \(X_t\)

Consider the following ARCH(1) model: \[ X_{t}=\sigma_{t}\epsilon_{t},\epsilon_{t}\sim\textrm{IID }N(0,1) \] \[ \sigma_{t}^{2}=0.1+0.9X_{t-1}^{2} \]

set.seed(1)
Xt <- garch.sim(alpha = c(0.1, 0.9), n = 1000)

1. Fitting \(\{X_t^2\}\) based on its ARMA representation:

\[ X_{t}^{2}=0.1+0.9X_{t-1}^{2}+\eta_{t},\eta_{t}\sim\textrm{WN} \]

arch1.arma <- arima(Xt^2, order = c(1,0,0), method = c("CSS"))
arch1.arma
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = Xt^2, order = c(1, 0, 0), method = c("CSS"))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1  intercept
##       0.7560     1.1218
## s.e.  0.0207     0.6860
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 28.01:  log likelihood = -3085.22,  aic = NA

2. Fitting \(\{X_t\}\) using conditional maximum likelihood method

arch1.mle <- garch(Xt, order = c(0,1), trace = F)
summary(arch1.mle)

Part 2 Monte Carlo Experiment for GARCH(1,1)

1. Estimating GARCH(1,1) model:

\[ X_{t}=\sigma_{t}\epsilon_{t},\epsilon_{t}\sim\textrm{IID }N(0,1) \] \[ \sigma_{t}^{2}=0.1+0.25X_{t-1}^{2}+0.25\sigma_{t-1}^{2} \]

set.seed(1)
data <- garch.sim(alpha = c(0.1, 0.25), beta = 0.25, n = 2500)
garch11 <- garch(data, order = c(1,1), trace = F)
summary(garch11)

2. Model diagnostics via graphical plots.

e <- garch11$residuals
esq <- e^2

ACF of \(\widehat{\epsilon}_t\)

rhoe <- acf(e, plot = F, na.action = na.pass)
alpha <- 0.95
conf.lims <- c(-1,1)*qnorm((1 + alpha)/2)/sqrt(rhoe$n.used)

acf.et <- rhoe$acf %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% mutate(lags = 1:n()) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = lags, y = V1)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,41,4)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = conf.lims, lty = 2, col = "blue") +
  labs(y = "ACF", x = "Lag", title = TeX("ACF of $\\widehat{\\epsilon}_t$")) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = lags, yend = 0)) + geom_point(size = 1) +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif")) +
  ylim(-0.1,0.1)
acf.et

Empirical distribution of \(\widehat{\epsilon}_t\)

fig12 <- ggplot(res, aes(et)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = 75, color="white", 
                 fill="dodgerblue3", 
                 alpha = 0.75, size = 0.1) + 
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, color = "darkred", size = 0.7,

QQ plot of \(\widehat{\epsilon}_t\) against \(N(0,1)\)

y <- quantile(res$et, c(0.25, 0.75), na.rm = T) 
x <- qnorm(c(0.25, 0.75))         
slope <- diff(y)/diff(x)             
int   <- y[1] - slope*x[1] 

fig13 <- ggplot(res, aes(sample = et)) +
  geom_qq(alpha = 0.5, size = 3, color = "dodgerblue3") +
  geom_abline(intercept=int, slope=slope, color = "darkred", size = 1) +
  labs(title = TeX("QQ Plot of $\\widehat{\\epsilon}_t$"), 
       x = "Normal Quantile", y = TeX("Quantile of $\\widehat{\\epsilon}_t$")) +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif"))

5. VaR based on GARCH(2,1)

TT <- length(Xt)
fore <- c(0,0,0)

for (t in (TT-100+1):TT) {
  
  garch21 <- garch(Xt[1:t], order = c(1,2), trace = F)
  a0 <- garch21$coef[1]; a1 <- garch21$coef[2]
  a2 <- garch21$coef[3]; b1 <- garch21$coef[4]
  
  sigma <- seq(0, 0, length = t)
  for (s in 3:t) {
    sigma[s] <- sqrt(a0 + a1*Xt[s-1]^2 + a2*Xt[s-2]^2 + b1*sigma[s-1]^2)
  }
  
  sigmat <- sigma[t]
  Qe <- quantile(garch21$residuals, probs = c(0.05, 0.025), na.rm = T)
  fore <- rbind(fore, c(sigmat*Qe[1], sigmat*Qe[2], Xt[t])*100)
  
}
fore <- fore[-1,]

fore.data <- data.frame(time = c(1:length(fore[,1])), fore1 = fore[,1], 
                        fore2 = fore[,2], fore3 = fore[,3])
VaR <- ggplot(fore.data, aes(time)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = fore1), size = 0.6, color = "dodgerblue3") +
  geom_line(aes(y = fore2), size = 0.6, color = "seagreen3") +
  geom_line(aes(y = fore3), size = 0.6, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "VaR of Goldman Sacks Daily Returns", 
       x = TeX("time"), y = TeX("Return")) +        
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", face = "bold"))
VaR
